Problem Number 1833 leetcode :-

It is a sweltering summer day, and a boy wants to buy some ice cream bars.

At the store, there are n ice cream bars. You are given an array costs of length n, where costs[i] is the price of the ith ice cream bar in coins. The boy initially has coins coins to spend, and he wants to buy as many ice cream bars as possible. 

Note: The boy can buy the ice cream bars in any order.

Return the maximum number of ice cream bars the boy can buy with coins coins.

You must solve the problem by counting sort.



Solution :-   C++

     class Solution {
public:
    int maxIceCream(vector<int>& costs, int coins) {
        int max_ = *max_element(costs.begin(), costs.end());
        vector<int>arr(max_ + 1, 0), ans(costs.size(), 0);
        for(int i = 0; i < costs.size(); i++){
            arr[costs[i]]++;
        }
        for(int i = 1; i <= max_; i++){
            arr[i] += arr[i - 1];
        }
        for(int i = costs.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--){
           ans[arr[costs[i]] - 1] = costs[i];
           arr[costs[i]]--;
        }
        int res = 0;
        for(int A : ans){
            if(A <= coins){
                coins -= A;
                res++;
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};




Explanation :-

This solution uses Counting Sort to sort costs without using sort().

Step 1: Count frequencies
arr[costs[i]]++;

arr[x] stores how many ice creams have cost x.

Step 2: Create prefix sums
arr[i] += arr[i - 1];

Now arr[x] tells how many elements are <= x.

Step 3: Build sorted array
ans[arr[costs[i]] - 1] = costs[i];
arr[costs[i]]--;

Places each cost in its correct sorted position (Counting Sort).

After this, ans becomes the sorted version of costs.

Example:

costs = [1,3,2,4,1]
ans   = [1,1,2,3,4]
Step 4: Buy cheapest ice creams first
for(int A : ans)
{
    if(A <= coins)
    {
        coins -= A;
        res++;
    }
}

Since ans is sorted, we keep buying the cheapest ice creams until we run out of coins.

Complexity
Time: O(n + maxCost)
Space: O(n + maxCost)

The main idea is: Counting Sort → Sorted Costs → Greedily buy cheapest ice creams first.
